# Performance stats — single-source-series methodology

Future contributors (human or AI) touching any surface that displays a
portfolio value, total return, Sharpe, CAGR, max drawdown, pct-weeks-beating,
or any benchmark comparative should read this first. It explains _why_ the
effective-series pattern exists and what keeps the displayed numbers
internally consistent.

## 1. The "single-source series" rule

For any portfolio + date range shown in the UI, there is exactly **one equity
path** — a list of `PerformanceSeriesPoint { date, aiPortfolio,
nasdaq100CapWeight, nasdaq100EqualWeight, sp500 }`. Every displayed number on
that surface — headline card, flip cards, tables, mini-charts, sidebar rows
— MUST be derived from that same series.

If a headline `$` value is drawn from series A and its accompanying `%` is
drawn from metrics computed off series B, they drift whenever the live tail
runs ahead of the server-cached snapshot. That has happened repeatedly on
`/platform/your-portfolios`, `/platform` (overview spotlight),
`/strategy-models/[slug]`, including its portfolio-values section. The fix is always the same:
**pick the effective series once,
recompute metrics from it, and thread that object through the entire
component tree.**

Whether the first visible point of that equity path renders as the model's
post-cost inception ($9,985) or as the viewer's investment size ($10,000) is
covered separately by §11; this section assumes that choice has already been
made and the same series is used everywhere on the page.

## 2. What "effective series" means

The daily snapshot is the canonical previous-close series. In steady state,
`effectiveDisplaySeries` is a pass-through to the server-computed
`displaySeries`, and every headline value reads the last point of that series.

The old client-side append/replace live-tail pattern is no longer a steady-state
UI mechanism. It is only acceptable as a brief stale-snapshot safety net for
bulk endpoints that explicitly emit `livePoint` while
`snapshot.asOfRunDate < latestRawRunDate`; once the cron rewrites
`portfolio_config_daily_series`, the snapshot's last point is the source of
truth again.

`buildLiveHoldingsAllocationResult(...)` in
[`src/lib/live-holdings-allocation.ts`](mdc:src/lib/live-holdings-allocation.ts)
computes `totalCurrentValue` as
`sum(weight_i × (notional / asOfPx_i) × latestPx_i)` in `mode: 'live'`. The
`notional` argument (aka `rebalanceDateNotional`) **MUST** be the **chart
series's** `aiPortfolio` **at the latest rebalance date** — the same
`run_date` whose snapshot supplies `weights`, `asOfPriceBySymbol`, and
holdings. After §11's display rebase the chart series is on the lifted
scale, and `buildLiveHoldingsAllocationResult` is scale-invariant
(`notional × Σ(weight_i × latestPx_i / asOfPx_i)`), so a lifted `notional`
produces a lifted `totalCurrentValue` that stays coherent with row-level
holdings values. It must
**not** be today's MTM, the chart's last `aiPortfolio`, or
`effectiveSeries[effectiveSeries.length - 1].aiPortfolio` (after
`continuous-daily-mtm-calendar`, that last point is already today's MTM;
passing it as `notional` double-counts rebalance→today price growth). This anti-pattern is independent of §11's display rebase — passing today's MTM as notional double-counts price growth on either scale.

The canonical accessor is `pts.find(p.date === latestRebalanceDate)?.aiPortfolio`,
with an on-or-before fallback; see `holdingsAllocationBaseNotional` in
[`src/components/platform/your-portfolio-client.tsx`](mdc:src/components/platform/your-portfolio-client.tsx)
and `spotlightHoldingsAllocationBaseNotional` in
[`src/components/platform/platform-overview-client.tsx`](mdc:src/components/platform/platform-overview-client.tsx).
`syncMissingConfigHoldingsSnapshots()`
([`src/lib/portfolio-config-holdings-write.ts`](mdc:src/lib/portfolio-config-holdings-write.ts))
self-heals `strategy_portfolio_config_holdings` gaps on **single-config**
read paths that read holdings directly — namely
`/api/platform/explore-portfolio-config-holdings` and
`ensureConfigDailySeries` in
[`src/lib/config-daily-series.ts`](mdc:src/lib/config-daily-series.ts).
**Do not** call it per-config on multi-config bulk endpoints
(`/api/platform/explore-portfolios-equity-series`,
`/api/platform/portfolio-configs-ranked`, etc.) — those rely on the cron
freshness invariant in §7 plus the bulk-read + `triggerPortfolioConfigsBatch`
recovery path described in §8.

## 3. The canonical derivation

The function that turns a series into the full metric bundle already exists:

```ts
// src/lib/config-performance-chart.ts
export function buildMetricsFromSeries(
  series: PerformanceSeriesPoint[],
  rebalanceFrequency: string,
  sharpeReturns: number[]
): {
  metrics: ConfigChartMetrics | null;
  fullMetrics: FullConfigPerformanceMetrics | null;
}
```

It returns:

- `totalReturn`, `cagr`, `maxDrawdown`, `endingValue`, `startingCapital`
- `sharpeRatio` (weekly-MTM) and `sharpeRatioDecisionCadence` (from
  `sharpeReturns`)
- `weeklyObservations`
- `pctWeeksBeatingNasdaq100`, `pctWeeksBeatingSp500`,
  `pctWeeksBeatingNasdaq100EqualWeight`
- `pctMonthsBeatingNasdaq100`
- `benchmarks.{nasdaq100CapWeight, nasdaq100EqualWeight,
  sp500}.{endingValue, totalReturn, cagr, maxDrawdown}`

Feeding this function the **effective** series instead of the raw one yields
`effectiveDisplayMetrics` — an internally-consistent bundle that the entire
page can consume without drift. Use the
`applyEffectiveSeriesToMetrics(serverMetrics, rawSeries, effectiveSeries,
rebalanceFrequency, sharpeReturns)` helper (also in
`config-performance-chart.ts`) so the reference-equality short-circuit is
shared across surfaces.

## 4. `sharpeReturns` — what to pass

`sharpeReturns` is the array of rebalance-cadence net returns used for
decision-cadence Sharpe; it is cadence-dimensional and must NOT be re-derived
from the effective series. Pass the existing `sharpeReturns` untouched when
recomputing. In steady state, the snapshot series already includes the latest
previous-close MTM point, so decision-cadence Sharpe stays tied to rebalance
events while `buildMetricsFromSeries` handles the weekly-MTM leg.

## 5. Benchmarks

Benchmark legs come from the same stored snapshot series as `aiPortfolio`.
Because the daily cron rewrites the snapshot after raw price and benchmark
ingestion, vs-benchmark comparatives compare like-for-like previous-close
snapshots. If a bulk endpoint emits a temporary stale-snapshot `livePoint`, its
benchmark legs must come from the same MTM path as
`buildConfigDailySeriesTailPoint`.

**Chart display vs payloads:** Snapshots, `buildMetricsFromSeries`, and API payloads still carry all four legs (`nasdaq100EqualWeight` included) for MTM, weekly beat rates, and flip-card stats. **Multi-line equity charts** (`PerformanceChart`, explore values chart, landing mini-charts) intentionally plot only `aiPortfolio`, `nasdaq100CapWeight`, and `sp500` and label the benchmarks as **Nasdaq-100** and **S&P 500** without “cap / equal” wording in the chart UI.

## 6. Price source (not intraday)

All portfolio and holding valuations use **previous-close** prices: the
holdings API sets `latestPriceBySymbol` from the max `run_date` in
`nasdaq_100_daily_raw` (same basis as `loadLatestRawRunDate` in the MTM walk).
There is **no** intraday quote fetch on any UI surface.

## 7. Data-side invariants (don't regress)

- `strategy_portfolio_config_holdings` must have a JSONB row for every
  `ai_run_batches.run_date` that falls within the config's cadence.
  `syncMissingConfigHoldingsSnapshots` fills gaps on demand.
- Cache invalidation on fill: delete the config's
  `portfolio_config_daily_series` row + `revalidateTag('mtm-walk-inputs')` and
  `revalidateTag('mtm-walk-inputs:' + strategyId)`. `revalidateTag` must be
  dynamically imported (`await import('next/cache')`) so this module can be
  pulled through the Client Component import graph.
- Holdings API and server MTM walk read the same stored snapshot, so the
  effective-tail basket equals the server basket.
- `rebaseSeriesForDisplay` ([`src/lib/config-daily-series.ts`](mdc:src/lib/config-daily-series.ts))
  is the canonical chart-display rebase helper. Anchors the four legs
  (`aiPortfolio`, `nasdaq100CapWeight`, `nasdaq100EqualWeight`, `sp500`)
  **independently** at `displayInitial` on the baseline date (no single
  shared scale factor across all four). `sliceAndScale` is a `@deprecated`
  wrapper that calls it. See §11 for when each anchor is used.
- `computeConfigDailySeries` must not persist `data_status='empty'` when
  `strategy_portfolio_config_performance` has rows for that config; if the
  in-memory rows array is empty but a head-count on the perf table is `> 0`,
  downgrade to `'early'` (DB maps to `'ready'`) instead of a sticky empty row.
- `ensureConfigDailySeries` must treat an existing snapshot with
  `data_status='empty'` as a cache-miss and recompute even when `asOfRunDate`
  matches `latestRawRunDate`. The per-request path rate-limits those recomputes
  per `(strategyId, configId)` (5 minutes) to avoid hot loops when upstream is
  genuinely empty.
- `refreshDailySeriesSnapshotsForStrategy` is the cron writer and MUST
  recompute every active config for the current `latestRawRunDate`; do not skip
  just because an existing snapshot has the same `asOfRunDate`. Raw prices for
  a given `run_date` can be corrected or re-ingested after the first snapshot
  write. The daily cron must invoke this refresh only after
  `nasdaq_100_daily_raw` and `benchmark_daily_prices` ingestion for the day.
- `buildLiveHoldingsAllocationResult` (`mode: 'live'`) requires
  `rebalanceDateNotional` to equal the **chart series's** `aiPortfolio` at
  the rebalance date that produced the snapshot in `asOfPriceBySymbol`.
  After `continuous-daily-mtm-calendar` the daily-series last point **is**
  today's MTM; using it as `notional` inflates row `currentValue` and
  `totalCurrentValue` by the rebalance→today growth factor (e.g. ~33% on a
  one-stock basket whose holding ran +33%). The function is scale-invariant
  in `notional`, so it works correctly whether the chart series is on the
  raw model scale or on §11's lifted scale; the rebalance-date anchor is
  what matters. On `/strategy-models`, mirror `holdingsAllocationBaseNotional`
  (include `holdingsRebalanceDates` in the `useMemo` deps that computes the
  notional).

## 8. Multi-config (explore) surfaces

Multi-config surfaces — `ExplorePortfoliosEquityChart`, portfolio pickers,
ranked cards, and any similar bulk-render view — cannot afford a per-config
live fetch on render. Per
[daily-snapshot-invariant](mdc:.cursor/rules/daily-snapshot-invariant.mdc),
they bulk-read `portfolio_config_daily_series` via `loadStrategyDailySeriesBulk`.
The stored series's last point IS the latest live-MTM point (produced by
`buildLatestMtmPointFromLastSnapshot` inside `computeConfigDailySeries`), and
the cron freshness invariant in §7 keeps that snapshot current.

For hypothetical $10k surfaces, the displayed latest-close value must converge:
the explore values chart last bar, `/strategy-models` page body,
`/strategy-models/[slug]#portfolio-values`, performance portfolio picker rows,
explore list cards, and explore detail dialog all read the same previous-close
value after §11's $10k display lift. User-rebased surfaces such as
`/platform/your-portfolios` and `/platform` overview use the same raw snapshot
source but rebase to `investmentSize` at `userStart`; compare those surfaces
only after normalizing for the same entry date and investment size.

If alignment between explore and single-config surfaces is required while
snapshots are stale, the server endpoint should compute **just the tail**
(`buildLatestMtmPointFromLastSnapshot(config)` — cheap, no full walk) for
each stale config and attach it to the payload. This is a temporary safety net
for the window before the cron snapshot rewrite, not the steady-state source of
truth. Fanning out `ensureConfigDailySeries()` per config is forbidden.

**Explore list + detail dialog (no extra ranked-API compute):** the
`/api/platform/explore-portfolios-equity-series` response includes optional
`livePoint` per `configId`. The explore client builds `livePointByConfigId` and
passes the matching `livePoint` into each list `ConfigCard` and as `liveTail`
on `ExplorePortfolioDetailDialog` only when the daily-series snapshot is stale.
In steady state those `livePoint` values are null and **headline portfolio $ /
total return** come from `RankedConfig.metrics.endingValuePortfolio`, matching
the values chart's $10k-lifted snapshot last point. Sharpe, CAGR, and max
drawdown on list cards also stay on the ranked snapshot
(`RankedConfig.metrics`).

**Two payload patterns:** `/api/platform/explore-portfolios-equity-series` emits
per-config `livePoint` with `date`, `aiPortfolio`, and optional benchmark fields
(`nasdaq100CapWeight`, `nasdaq100EqualWeight`, `sp500`) only for stale
snapshots. `/api/platform/portfolio-configs-ranked` emits `RankedConfig.metrics`
from `portfolio_config_daily_series`, but
`loadPortfolioConfigsRankedPayload` first replaces
`endingValuePortfolio`, `endingValueMarket`,
`endingValueNasdaq100EqualWeight`, and `endingValueSp500` with the last point
of `rebaseSeriesForDisplay(snapshot.series, { displayInitial: 10_000 })`.
Persisted snapshot metrics remain raw model-NAV; the ranked API response is
display-anchored. Scale-invariant fields (`totalReturn`, `cagr`,
`sharpeRatio`, `maxDrawdown`, beat rates, observations) stay unchanged.

Consumers that **aggregate across configs**
(`/api/platform/strategy-models-ranked`, landing-page `ExperimentSection`,
`ModelHeaderCard` on `/strategy-models/[slug]`, explore filters such as
`filterBeatSp500`) intentionally do not use a per-request overlay; they are
coherent because the daily cron rewrites the snapshot after price and benchmark
ingestion and then revalidates caches. They should treat
`RankedConfig.metrics.endingValue*` as already display-anchored and must not
apply another 15 bps lift or haircut.

## 9. When to use this rule

Touch this rule any time you:

- Add or modify a number (`$`, `%`, ratio) displayed on `/strategy-models/[slug]`,
  `/platform/your-portfolios`, `/platform` overview,
  `/platform/explore-portfolios`, portfolio picker rows, or
  `/strategy-models/[slug]#portfolio-values`.
- Change `buildLatestMtmPointFromLastSnapshot`,
  `buildLiveHoldingsAllocationResult`, `buildMetricsFromSeries`,
  `loadPortfolioConfigsRankedPayload`, or `syncMissingConfigHoldingsSnapshots`.
- Wire a new client component to a portfolio performance payload.

The landing page (`/`) is out of scope for the **same-page selected-portfolio
checklist** in §10, but not for the ranked-metric display contract: any landing
page card that consumes `RankedConfig.metrics.endingValue*` receives those
values already lifted by `/api/platform/portfolio-configs-ranked`. Its
performance carousel uses the same `portfolio_config_daily_series` source. If a
future change adds a **single-config** headline `$` or total return % on `/`,
that surface must follow §2–§4 (effective series threaded through the component
tree).

## 10. Same-page convergence checklist (manual PR review)

For one selected portfolio with **Today** holdings, every **dollar** and
**total return %** on the same page must agree:

- **`/strategy-models/[slug]`:** Key-metrics FlipCard headline; At-a-glance
  “Portfolio value”; overview `PerformanceChart` last point; holdings
  `HoldingsPortfolioValueLine`; holdings table row $ (sum = line). Headline
  values and charts use `effectivePerformanceDisplaySeries` /
  `effectiveDisplayMetrics`, which pass through the rebased snapshot series in
  steady state. Any holdings-row valuation that calls
  `buildLiveHoldingsAllocationResult(...)` must anchor `notional` at the
  **latest rebalance date** per §2, never at the chart's last point.
- **`/platform/your-portfolios`:** Main portfolio value card; sidebar row
  override when selected; holdings line; `PerformanceChart` `initialNotional`
  from effective series first point; vs-benchmark stats from
  `effectiveDisplaySeries` / `effectiveDisplayMetrics` (no mixed API-only
  excess returns).
- **`/platform` overview:** Spotlight portfolio value, chart, holdings line,
  and the **matching** overview tile (same profile id) use the same effective
  spotlight series; other tiles show an explicit “As of close · …” date from
  raw `cardState.series` last point.
- **`/platform/explore-portfolios`:** List card Value ($ / %), values chart
  last point, and detail dialog headline use the same snapshot last point;
  `livePoint` is only a stale-snapshot safety net.

Invariant: `applyEffectiveSeriesToMetrics(...).endingValue ===
effectiveSeries[effectiveSeries.length - 1].aiPortfolio` (see
`src/lib/config-performance-chart.test.ts`).

Additional invariant from §11: every surface above shows the **same first-bar
dollars** for the same portfolio + entry date + investment size — `$10,000`
on hypothetical surfaces (`/strategy-models/[slug]`, `/platform/explore-portfolios`)
and `investmentSize` on user-rebased surfaces (`/platform/your-portfolios`,
`/platform` overview, guest preview). Differences between any two surfaces
on the same portfolio's portfolio value or total return % are a regression
of §11.

## 11. Display anchor — every chart's first point is the dollars you put in

Underlying simulation math is unchanged: model series in
`portfolio_config_daily_series` and `portfolio_strategy_daily_series` anchor
at $9,985 = `INITIAL_CAPITAL × (1 − 15 bps)` at model inception, and live
MTM values from `buildLiveHoldingsAllocationResult` and
`buildLatestMtmPointFromLastSnapshot` are produced in those same model
dollars. The 15 bps entry trade cost is a real economic event and stays in
the simulation.

The **chart-display** layer reanchors the series so the first visible point
renders at the dollars the viewer is mentally putting in:

- Hypothetical surfaces (`/strategy-models/[slug]`,
  `/platform/explore-portfolios`): first point = `INITIAL_CAPITAL` ($10,000).
- User-rebased surfaces (`/platform/your-portfolios`, `/platform` overview,
  guest preview): first point = `investmentSize` at `userStart`.

Canonical helpers in `src/lib/config-daily-series.ts`:
`rebaseSeriesForDisplay(series, { anchorDate?, displayInitial })` and
`liftTailPointForDisplay(rawFirst, tail, displayInitial)` for a single MTM
tail row. Per-leg independent
scale (matches §7). Walks back to a `≤ anchorDate` baseline and prepends a
synthetic point at exactly `anchorDate` when no snapshot row lands there;
the synthetic point's four legs are all `displayInitial`, and subsequent
points are scaled by the per-leg factor of the baseline so each benchmark
preserves co-movement.

Any temporary stale-snapshot `livePoint` from §8 must be lifted by the same
per-leg factor as the rest of the series before it is used. Server endpoints
lift before returning JSON:

- `/api/platform/portfolio-config-performance`
- `/api/platform/portfolio-configs-ranked` / `loadPortfolioConfigsRankedPayload`
  — lift `RankedConfig.metrics.endingValuePortfolio` and the benchmark
  `endingValue*` legs to the $10k display anchor by per-leg-rebasing
  `snapshot.series` with `rebaseSeriesForDisplay`. Build
  `benchmarkEndingValues` / `liveTail.benchmark` from the same lifted last
  point. Persisted `portfolio_config_daily_series.metrics` stays in raw
  model-NAV dollars; ranking payloads lift once at the API boundary because
  picker rows, explore cards, explore detail, and cross-config rank/comparison
  helpers divide these ending values by `INITIAL_CAPITAL`.
- `/api/platform/explore-portfolios-equity-series` (lifts both series and
  `livePoint`; `notionalSeries` passed to `buildConfigDailySeriesTailPoint`
  remains the **raw** snapshot to keep that helper in model dollars)
- `/api/platform/explore-portfolio-config-holdings` — optional `livePoint` is
  lifted to the same **inception $10k** display scale via
  `liftTailPointForDisplay` (per-leg factors from `snapshot.series[0]`).
  User-anchored pages should prefer the snapshot series in steady state rather
  than appending a per-request chart tail.
- `/api/platform/user-portfolio-performance`
- `buildGuestUserEntryPerformancePayload`

The 15 bps cost surfaces as a slight drag in the line's slope, NOT as a
different starting dollar. Headline portfolio value, cards, tooltips, and
chart all consume the rebased series, so dollar figures agree across pages
for the same portfolio + entry date + investment size.

**Forbidden:** any `× (1 − 15 bps)` factor on display dollars. The constant
`USER_ENTRY_TRANSACTION_COST_RATE` no longer exists in
`config-performance-chart.ts` or `portfolio-movement.ts`. Do not reintroduce
it. The simulation-side equivalent (`transactionCostBps = 15` in
`portfolio-config-compute-core.ts` and `TRANSACTION_COST_RATE` in
`live-mark-to-market.ts`) is the only acceptable home for that magic number.

**Required: same effective series everywhere on a page.** Combine §2 (live
tail) with this rule: lift first, then apply effective-series logic.
`buildMetricsFromSeries` is called on the lifted series so `endingValue` /
`startingCapital` reflect lifted dollars; total return %, CAGR, max
drawdown, Sharpe, beat-rates are scale-invariant and are unchanged by the
lift.
